# Reflection Questions

## 1. Why did you use inheritance?

I used inheritance because all the different transports are types of
vehicles. They all share the same base behavior, so I created a
`Vehicle` base class and let `Car`, `Airplane`, `Boat`, and `Helicopter`
inherit from it. This makes the code more organized and allows all of
them to be treated as `Vehicle` objects through polymorphism.

## 2. Why did you use interfaces?

I used interfaces to represent what a vehicle can do. For example, a car
can drive, an airplane can fly, and a boat can sail. Interfaces allow
different classes to have the same capability without forcing them to
inherit from another class. This makes the design more flexible.

## 3. Could Helicopter inherit from both Vehicle and Airplane? Why or why not?

No. In C#, a class can inherit from only one base class. Since
`Helicopter` already inherits from `Vehicle`, it cannot also inherit
from `Airplane`. If it needs additional behaviors, it should implement
interfaces instead.

## 4. Why can Helicopter implement both IFlyable and IDriveable?

A class in C# can implement multiple interfaces. Since the challenge
requires a helicopter to both fly and drive, it can implement both
`IFlyable` and `IDriveable` while still inheriting from the `Vehicle`
base class.

## 5. If a Submarine can both sail and dive, how would you design it?

I would make `Submarine` inherit from `Vehicle` because it is a vehicle.
Then I would implement `ISailable` and create another interface such as
`IDiveable` so it can both sail and dive. This keeps the design
organized and follows the idea that inheritance describes what an object
is, while interfaces describe what it can do.
